---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import ReadingProgressBar from '../components/ReadingProgressBar.astro';
import CountryEntrepreneurshipTable from '../components/widgets/CountryEntrepreneurshipTable.astro';
import countries from '../components/widgets/country-entrepreneurship-scores.json';

const title = "Ranking Every Country on Business Freedom, Hiring, Taxes, and Property Rights";
const description = "184 countries ranked on a weighted score built from four questions: is it easy to start a company, easy to hire and fire, is the tax burden onerous, and can you own an asset without it getting seized.";
const pubDate = "July 3, 2026";

const top10 = countries.slice(0, 10);
const bottom10 = countries.slice(-10).reverse();
---

<html lang="en">
<head>
  <BaseHead title={title} description={description} />
  <style>
    .article-container {
      display: flex;
      justify-content: center;
      max-width: 1080px;
      margin: 0 auto;
    }
    .wrap {
      max-width: 900px;
      margin: 0 auto;
      padding: 0 1.25rem 5rem;
      width: 100%;
      box-sizing: border-box;
    }

    .article-header {
      padding: 2.5rem 0 2rem;
      border-bottom: 3px solid var(--accent);
      margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
    }
    .article-header .meta {
      font-family: var(--font-body);
      font-size: 0.82rem;
      color: rgb(var(--gray));
      margin: 0 0 1rem;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    }
    .article-header h1 {
      font-size: clamp(1.6rem, 4.5vw, 2.6rem);
      margin: 0 0 1.2rem;
      font-family: var(--font-heading);
      line-height: 1.15;
      font-weight: 800;
      color: rgb(var(--black));
    }
    .article-header .intro {
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      line-height: 1.6;
      color: rgb(var(--gray-dark));
      margin: 0;
    }

    .prose {
      font-size: 1.05rem;
      line-height: 1.75;
      color: rgb(var(--gray-dark));
    }
    .prose p {
      margin: 0 0 1.5rem;
    }
    .prose h2 {
      font-family: var(--font-heading);
      font-size: 1.7rem;
      color: rgb(var(--black));
      margin: 2.5rem 0 1.25rem;
      line-height: 1.2;
    }
    .prose h3 {
      font-family: var(--font-heading);
      font-size: 1.2rem;
      color: rgb(var(--black));
      margin: 2rem 0 0.75rem;
      line-height: 1.25;
    }
    .prose hr {
      border: 0;
      border-top: 1px solid rgb(var(--gray-light));
      margin: 3rem 0;
    }
    .prose blockquote {
      margin: 1.5rem 0;
      padding: 0.25rem 0 0.25rem 1.25rem;
      border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
      color: rgb(var(--gray-dark));
      font-style: italic;
    }
    .prose blockquote p {
      margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
    }
    .prose blockquote p:last-child {
      margin-bottom: 0;
    }

    /* Weight table */
    .weight-table {
      width: 100%;
      border-collapse: collapse;
      margin: 1.5rem 0;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
    }
    .weight-table th,
    .weight-table td {
      text-align: left;
      padding: 0.65rem 0.8rem;
      border-bottom: 1px solid rgb(var(--gray-light));
    }
    .weight-table th {
      font-family: var(--font-heading);
      font-size: 0.75rem;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.06em;
      color: rgb(var(--gray));
    }
    .weight-table td.weight-num {
      font-weight: 700;
      color: rgb(var(--black));
    }

    /* Top/bottom cards */
    .rank-grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
      gap: 0.5rem 1.5rem;
      margin: 1.5rem 0;
    }
    .rank-row {
      display: flex;
      justify-content: space-between;
      padding: 0.5rem 0;
      border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(var(--gray-light), 0.7);
      font-size: 0.95rem;
    }
    .rank-row .rank-num {
      color: rgb(var(--gray));
      font-weight: 700;
      width: 1.75rem;
      display: inline-block;
    }
    .rank-row .rank-name {
      color: rgb(var(--black));
      font-weight: 600;
    }
    .rank-row .rank-score {
      color: rgb(var(--gray-dark));
      font-family: var(--font-ui), sans-serif;
    }
    @media (max-width: 640px) {
      .rank-grid {
        grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      }
    }

    .caveat-list {
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      line-height: 1.65;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <ReadingProgressBar />
  <Header />
  <main>
    <div class="article-container">
      <div class="wrap">

        <header class="article-header">
          <p class="meta">{pubDate}</p>
          <h1>{title}</h1>
          <p class="intro">{description}</p>
        </header>

        <section class="prose">
          <p>
            The pitch for why some places produce startups and some places do not usually starts with talent
            and culture. But there is a third piece that gets less attention: the actual legal environment. Here
            is the framework I used to build this ranking.
          </p>

          <blockquote>
            <p>
              And like, by the way, many countries have that that don't have a Silicon Valley. And what are
              they missing? They're missing the other two components. The second is, do you have a set of
              laws and policies that facilitate entrepreneurship or essentially good for business? Like, can
              you create a company easily? Can you hire people easily? Can you fire people easily? Is there a
              tax incentive structure that's not onerous? Can you own, and this is a big one lately, which
              California is kind of moving against, but can you own an illiquid asset that has value or will
              it get seized?
            </p>
          </blockquote>

          <p>
            That is four testable questions: is it easy to start and run a business, is it easy to hire and
            fire, is the tax structure reasonable, and are your property rights actually secure. The
            <a href="https://static.heritage.org/index/pdf/2026/2026_indexofeconomicfreedom.pdf">2026 Index of Economic Freedom</a>
            from the Heritage Foundation grades 184 economies on twelve sub-scores every year, and four of
            them map almost exactly onto those four questions: Business Freedom, Labor Freedom, Tax Burden,
            and Property Rights. So I pulled those four sub-scores for every graded country and combined them
            into one weighted number.
          </p>

          <h2>How it's weighted</h2>
          <p>
            The weighting is not scientific. It is proportional to how much emphasis each idea got in the
            quote above: hiring and firing get asked about as two separate questions, so labor freedom counts
            for the most. Property rights get an explicit "this is a big one lately" callout, so they are
            weighted just behind labor. Business freedom and tax burden get one clause each.
          </p>

          <table class="weight-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Factor</th>
                <th>What it measures</th>
                <th>Weight</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>Hire / fire freedom</td>
                <td>Labor Freedom sub-score: how easy it is to hire and to fire</td>
                <td class="weight-num">30%</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Business freedom</td>
                <td>Business Freedom sub-score: how easy it is to start, run, and close a company</td>
                <td class="weight-num">25%</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Property rights</td>
                <td>Property Rights sub-score: how secure ownership of an asset is from seizure</td>
                <td class="weight-num">25%</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Tax burden</td>
                <td>Tax Burden sub-score: how much of income and corporate profit the state takes</td>
                <td class="weight-num">20%</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>

          <p>
            Every sub-score runs 0 to 100, where 100 is the most free. The composite score below is just
            the weighted average of the four, so it also runs roughly 0 to 100.
          </p>

          <hr />

          <h2>Top 10</h2>
          <div class="rank-grid">
            {top10.map((c) => (
              <div class="rank-row">
                <span><span class="rank-num">{c.rank}</span><span class="rank-name">{c.name}</span></span>
                <span class="rank-score">{c.composite.toFixed(1)}</span>
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>

          <h2>Bottom 10</h2>
          <div class="rank-grid">
            {bottom10.map((c) => (
              <div class="rank-row">
                <span><span class="rank-num">{c.rank}</span><span class="rank-name">{c.name}</span></span>
                <span class="rank-score">{c.composite.toFixed(1)}</span>
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>

          <p>
            The United States lands at number 2, mostly on strong property rights and business freedom.
            Norway and Finland show up near the top despite genuinely high tax burdens, both scoring below
            the 184-country average on that factor alone. What pulls them up is near-perfect property rights
            and business freedom scores that outweigh the tax penalty once the four factors are combined.
            Mauritius, at number 4, is the highest-ranked country in Africa and one people rarely name when
            they talk about "good for business."
          </p>

          <hr />

          <h2>Full ranking</h2>

          <CountryEntrepreneurshipTable />

          <hr />

          <h2>Methodology and what's missing</h2>
          <ul class="caveat-list">
            <li>
              Source data is the Heritage Foundation's
              <a href="https://static.heritage.org/index/pdf/2026/2026_indexofeconomicfreedom.pdf">2026 Index of Economic Freedom</a>,
              which grades 176 economies with a full composite score and reports component sub-scores for
              8 additional "not graded" economies (Afghanistan, Iraq, Libya, Liechtenstein, Somalia, Syria,
              Ukraine, and Yemen). Those 8 are included here because their Business Freedom, Labor Freedom,
              Tax Burden, and Property Rights sub-scores are all reported even though Heritage does not
              publish an overall grade for them.
            </li>
            <li>
              13 sovereign states are not rated by Heritage and are not in this ranking: Andorra, Antigua and
              Barbuda, Grenada, the Marshall Islands, Monaco, Nauru, Palau, Palestine, Saint Kitts and Nevis,
              San Marino, South Sudan, Tuvalu, and Vatican City. Hong Kong, which Heritage rated for decades,
              has also been dropped from the index since 2021.
            </li>
            <li>
              The weighting is a reading of the quote above, not a Heritage Foundation product. Heritage does
              not endorse this composite or the weights applied to it.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</body>
</html>
